04769nam a22007215i 9780292795204DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927952047 a10.7560/7213402doi  a(DE-B1597)588070  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGE180b.M56 1995eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a363.7/56/09732201 aBökönyi, Sándor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chora of Metaponto 2 :bArchaeozoology at Pantanello and Five Other Sites /cSándor Bökönyi, Erika Gál; ed. by László Bartosiewicz. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tSpecial Acknowledgment -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Animal Husbandry from the Late Neolithic through the Roman Period -- t2 Animal Husbandry in Roman Metaponto -- t3 Taphonomic Analysis of Bone Remains from the Chora of Metaponto -- t4 Bird Remains from the Chora of Metaponto -- t5 Bone Artifacts from the Chora of Metaponto -- tAppendix: Bone Measurements -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1974 to the present, the Institute of Classical Archaeology at the University of Texas at Austin has carried out archaeological excavations in the ancient territory (chora) of Metaponto, now located in the modern province of Basilicata on the southern coast of Italy. This wide-ranging investigation, which covers a number of sites and a time period ranging from prehistory to the Roman Empire, has unearthed a wealth of new information about the ancient rural economy in southern Italy. These discoveries will be published in a multi-volume series titled The Chora of Metaponto. This volume on archaeozoology—the study of animal remains from archaeological sites—is the second in the series, following The Chora of Metaponto: The Necropoleis (1998). Archaeozoology at Pantanello and Five Other Sites describes the animal remains found throughout Metaponto and discusses what they reveal about ancient practices of hunting and herding, domestication and importation of new breeds, people's attitudes toward animals, and what animal remains indicate about past environments. A chapter devoted to bird bones, which are a relatively rare find because of their fragility, provides high quality information on the environment and methods of fowling, as well as on the beliefs and symbolism associated with birds. The final chapter covers tools—some simple, others sophisticated and richly decorated—made from animal bones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAnimal culturezItalyzMetaponto RegionxHistory. 0aAnimal remains (Archaeology)zItalyzMetaponto Region. 0aEnvironmental policyzUnited States. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zItalyzMetaponto Region. 0aHistoric siteszItalyzMetaponto Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBartosiewicz, László, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartosiewicz, László, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBökönyi, Sándor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Joseph Coleman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGál, Erika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGál, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795204/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE